00:11:22.391 --> 00:11:24.101
Oh. God. no!

251
00:11:24.184 --> 00:11:26.019
It was on board
the Floatwell!

252
00:11:26.103 --> 00:11:27.563
(gasps)
The ship that sank

253
00:11:27.646 --> 00:11:29.857
in that horrible
space storm?

254
00:11:29.940 --> 00:11:33.443
Yes. I'm afraid your friend's
derriere is lost forever

255
00:11:33.527 --> 00:11:36.113
in the depths
of the Sargaseous Sea.

256
00:11:36.196 --> 00:11:37.364
My ass!

257
00:11:37.447 --> 00:11:39.324
Sweet love of my life!

258
00:11:39.408 --> 00:11:42.870
Several hundred people
died. too. including my wife.

259
00:11:42.953 --> 00:11:45.080
My ass!

260
00:11:45.163 --> 00:11:46.540
I'm sorry. buddy.

261
00:11:46.623 --> 00:11:47.958
Maybe we can get
you a new one.

262
00:11:48.041 --> 00:11:49.418
Never!

263
00:11:49.501 --> 00:11:51.545
My ass is my soul mate.

264
00:11:51.628 --> 00:11:53.547
It even has
its own hind-brain.

265
00:11:53.630 --> 00:11:56.717
- Really? Your butt can think?
- No.

266
00:11:56.800 --> 00:11:58.177
But it can feel.

267
00:11:58.260 --> 00:12:00.888
And right now.
it's hind-heartbroken!

268
00:12:00.971 --> 00:12:03.765
Just like me!
(sobbing)

269
00:12:03.849 --> 00:12:06.018
Wow. Bender.

270
00:12:06.101 --> 00:12:08.353
this is really important
to you. isn't it?

271
00:12:08.437 --> 00:12:09.646
(crying)
Uh-huh.

272
00:12:09.730 --> 00:12:12.649
Okay. we're gonna
find that shipwreck

273
00:12:12.733 --> 00:12:15.110
and get you your
backside back.

274
00:12:15.194 --> 00:12:18.322
(stops crying)
Okay. let's go.

275
00:12:22.826 --> 00:12:25.829
(engine whooshing)

276
00:12:32.002 --> 00:12:33.754
The ship carrying
Bender's heinie

277
00:12:33.837 --> 00:12:36.757
sank in the treacherous gases
of the Sargaseous Sea.

278
00:12:36.840 --> 00:12:38.675
Once we locate the wreck...
(screams)

279
00:12:38.759 --> 00:12:40.677
Asteroids!

280
00:12:40.761 --> 00:12:46.475
(dramatic music playing)

281
00:12:46.558 --> 00:12:48.352
LEELA: Curse this
interstellar fog.

282
00:12:48.435 --> 00:12:51.438
Why isn't there a lighthouse
to guide us away from the rocks?

283
00:12:51.522 --> 00:12:53.732
I don't know. but look out
for that lighthouse!

284
00:12:53.815 --> 00:12:55.359
(all scream)

285
00:12:59.613 --> 00:13:01.698
(lighthouse keeper panting)

286
00:13:01.782 --> 00:13:05.118
(all groaning)

287
00:13:05.202 --> 00:13:06.745
So you're alive. are ye?

288
00:13:06.828 --> 00:13:09.248
(groans)
I suppose you'll be wanting

289
00:13:09.331 --> 00:13:10.916
to keep your tooth fillin's.

290
00:13:10.999 --> 00:13:14.753
- Are ye hurt?
- No. but we could use a hug.

291
00:13:14.837 --> 00:13:17.339
Better come inside then.

292
00:13:20.467 --> 00:13:21.969
Name's Tarquin.

293
00:13:22.052 --> 00:13:23.762
Been alone here.
tending this light.

294
00:13:23.846 --> 00:13:26.515
- longer'n I can remember.
- (bell dings)

295
00:13:26.598 --> 00:13:28.183
That'll be my Cup-a-Soup.

296
00:13:28.267 --> 00:13:31.144
It's been microwavin'
longer'n I can remember.

297
00:13:31.228 --> 00:13:32.813
This is a dangerous coast.

298
00:13:32.896 --> 00:13:35.274
We didn't see your light
until it was too late.

299
00:13:35.357 --> 00:13:38.026
No beam can pierce
that devilish mist.

300
00:13:38.110 --> 00:13:39.862
Shipwrecks be so common.

301
00:13:39.945 --> 00:13:42.489
I make a good livin'
out of whatever washes ashore.

302
00:13:42.573 --> 00:13:44.867
Found me
a whole Blue Man Group once.

303
00:13:44.950 --> 00:13:46.577
So you have two jobs?

304
00:13:46.660 --> 00:13:50.372
More. I also salvage
the wrecks with my bathysphere.

305
00:13:50.455 --> 00:13:51.832
and I'm a butcher.

306
00:13:51.915 --> 00:13:54.585
if you like blue meat.

307
00:13:54.668 --> 00:13:57.171
Sounds good.
but about that bathysphere.

308
00:13:57.254 --> 00:13:59.256
We want to salvage
a cargo ship that sank

309
00:13:59.339 --> 00:14:01.008
carrying this
robot's rear end.

310
00:14:01.091 --> 00:14:04.595
Aye. I'll help ye
for a cut of the booty.

311
00:14:04.678 --> 00:14:07.389
Now. when you say
"a cut of the booty"...

312
00:14:07.472 --> 00:14:10.434
I mean a percentage of the value
of the recovered goods.

313
00:14:10.517 --> 00:14:14.521
Now be gettin' some rest.
The booty call is at daybreak.

314
00:14:14.605 --> 00:14:20.652
(dramatic music playing)

315
00:14:36.877 --> 00:14:39.796
(Tarquin panting)

316
00:14:39.880 --> 00:14:42.883
(grunting)

317
00:14:55.562 --> 00:14:58.106
(hissing)

318
00:15:06.990 --> 00:15:09.368
(screaming)

319
00:15:09.451 --> 00:15:11.870
TARQUIN (over radio): Those sound like
one-eyed corpse screams.

320
00:15:11.954 --> 00:15:14.957
Oh. I wish I was down there
with ye.

321
00:15:17.084 --> 00:15:19.044
Let's not forget
that this shipwreck

322
00:15:19.127 --> 00:15:23.090
is also the final resting place
of this brave captain.

323
00:15:23.173 --> 00:15:26.385
Place your bets.
Whee!

324
00:15:34.601 --> 00:15:36.562
BENDER: (gasps)
That's it. I'm sure!

325
00:15:36.645 --> 00:15:38.438
I can tell by the
words on the crate!

326
00:15:38.522 --> 00:15:40.524
(Bender grunts)

327
00:15:40.607 --> 00:15:42.109
Oh. my beloved.

328
00:15:42.192 --> 00:15:44.570
You complete me.

329
00:15:47.573 --> 00:15:50.576
(thunder crashing)

330
00:15:52.828 --> 00:15:55.622
Hurry on inside now.
Storm's a-brewin'.

331
00:15:55.706 --> 00:15:57.666
I can feel it
in my Weather Channel app.

332
00:15:57.749 --> 00:15:59.126
(phone buzzing)

333
00:15:59.209 --> 00:16:01.670
(thunder continues)

334
00:16:01.753 --> 00:16:04.715
Soon the sea will be belchin'
her dead upon the shore.

335
00:16:04.798 --> 00:16:07.467
If ye like your shoes unmatched
and with feet still in 'em.

336
00:16:07.551 --> 00:16:10.637
this is your night.

337
00:16:10.721 --> 00:16:13.515
(whirring)

338
00:16:14.850 --> 00:16:16.351
Can't you make the beacon
any brighter?

339
00:16:16.435 --> 00:16:18.520
Nay. 'tis already
the brightest object

340
00:16:18.604 --> 00:16:20.939
in the known universe.
and even so.

341
00:16:21.023 --> 00:16:24.526
it can't be seen three feet
away in a storm like this.

342
00:16:24.610 --> 00:16:30.449
(eerie music playing)

343
00:16:30.532 --> 00:16:32.242
I thought we were
near the rocks.

344
00:16:32.326 --> 00:16:34.036
but I don't see
the lighthouse.

345
00:16:34.119 --> 00:16:36.205
so everything is fine
and we can relax.

346
00:16:36.288 --> 00:16:40.334
All hands on deck
for mojitos.

347
00:16:40.417 --> 00:16:43.670
The important thing is
I got my final piece back.

348
00:16:43.754 --> 00:16:45.464
Hey. Fry.
take a picture of me

349
00:16:45.547 --> 00:16:47.341
biting my own
shiny metal ass.

350
00:16:47.424 --> 00:16:48.884
I'd be honored.

351
00:16:48.967 --> 00:16:51.970
(camera shutter clicking)

352
00:16:58.477 --> 00:17:02.523
(sighs) You muddled the mint
well. Alejandro.

353
00:17:06.193 --> 00:17:08.570
- The lighthouse! Dead ahead!
- Aye!

354
00:17:12.574 --> 00:17:14.952
(camera shutter
continues clicking)

355
00:17:15.035 --> 00:17:17.412
Well. I'm sure
Bender's fanny is tired.

356
00:17:17.496 --> 00:17:20.499
As soon as this storm passes.
let's be on our way.

357
00:17:20.582 --> 00:17:22.459
(radio static)
Sargaseous lighthouse.

358
00:17:22.543 --> 00:17:25.087
this is
the S.S. Miami Muy Caliente.

359
00:17:25.170 --> 00:17:27.005
Thank you
for your glorious beacon.

360
00:17:27.089 --> 00:17:30.509
It saved our lives
and our Saturday night.

361
00:17:30.592 --> 00:17:32.135
Adios.

362
00:17:32.219 --> 00:17:34.930
(Caribbean music playing)

363
00:17:35.013 --> 00:17:36.557
Your aft-plate.

364
00:17:36.640 --> 00:17:39.977
Its fiery gleam saved a ship
full of South Beach swabbies.

365
00:17:40.060 --> 00:17:41.895
Well. I do polish it
every day.

366
00:17:41.979 --> 00:17:43.897
and I sleep in
a chamois diaper.

367
00:17:43.981 --> 00:17:45.941
It's a hundred times
more reflective

368
00:17:46.024 --> 00:17:47.693
than the mirror in my beacon.

369
00:17:47.776 --> 00:17:49.778
Might I keep it
for the lighthouse?

370
00:17:49.862 --> 00:17:51.280
What?! No!

371
00:17:51.363 --> 00:17:54.366
But. Bender. your buttocks
could save lives.

372
00:17:54.449 --> 00:17:55.701
I hate lives!

373
00:17:55.784 --> 00:17:57.953
These are sailors' lives.
Bender.

374
00:17:58.036 --> 00:18:00.080
Think of the untold cursing
that would be lost

375
00:18:00.163 --> 00:18:03.542
to future generations.
Could you live with that?

376
00:18:03.625 --> 00:18:05.961
(crying)

377
00:18:06.044 --> 00:18:10.215
You know the answer.
you scurvy bastard!

378
00:18:10.299 --> 00:18:14.386
Maybe I have been selfish.
hiding my ass under a bushel.

379
00:18:14.469 --> 00:18:16.638
Perhaps.
like all great men.

380
00:18:16.722 --> 00:18:19.933
my ass has a destiny.
and if it does.

381
00:18:20.017 --> 00:18:22.811
I can't stand in its way.

382
00:18:25.230 --> 00:18:27.900
(whirring slows to a stop)

383
00:18:27.983 --> 00:18:29.985
(thunder crashing)

384
00:18:30.068 --> 00:18:33.071
(whirring)

385
00:18:39.369 --> 00:18:45.375
(somber music playing)

386
00:19:00.098 --> 00:19:02.226
Bender. come join us.

387
00:19:02.309 --> 00:19:03.977
We're watching Rear Window.

388
00:19:04.061 --> 00:19:07.064
I used to stick my rear
out the window.

389
00:19:07.147 --> 00:19:10.192
If you prefer.
we could watch Behind the Music.

390
00:19:10.275 --> 00:19:12.653
My behind
used to make music.

391
00:19:12.736 --> 00:19:14.029
Backdraft is on.

392
00:19:14.112 --> 00:19:16.114
Even my ass
wouldn't watch that.

393
00:19:16.198 --> 00:19:19.743
Bender. I'm proud of you
for the sacrifice you made.

394
00:19:19.826 --> 00:19:23.121
Try and find solace in the fact
that somewhere out there.

395
00:19:23.205 --> 00:19:26.208
your keister is doing good.

396
00:19:30.045 --> 00:19:32.005
(somber music playing)

397
00:19:32.089 --> 00:19:33.757
Well. my shiny friend.

398
00:19:33.841 --> 00:19:35.634
yer days of carousin' are over.

399
00:19:35.717 --> 00:19:38.720
but yer nights of endless.
monotonous rotatin'

400
00:19:38.804 --> 00:19:39.972
have just begun.

401
00:19:40.055 --> 00:19:42.558
Now what say I read you
a nice passage

402
00:19:42.641 --> 00:19:46.019
from the scripture to help you
forget yer old master?

403
00:19:51.275 --> 00:19:55.362
"In the sanctuary. he made
two cherubim of olive-wood.

404
00:19:55.445 --> 00:19:57.739
each ten cubits high.

405
00:19:57.823 --> 00:19:59.992
(echoing) And one wing
measured five cubits.

406
00:20:00.075 --> 00:20:03.287
and the other wing measured
five cubits; from the tip..."

407
00:20:03.370 --> 00:20:05.372
(gasps)

408
00:20:14.256 --> 00:20:18.093
Oh. no! Our son Johnny
fell down the gravity well!

409
00:20:23.599 --> 00:20:26.268
JOHNNY: Thank you. Assie.

410
00:20:26.351 --> 00:20:30.981
(somber music playing)

411
00:20:31.064 --> 00:20:32.983
(knocking)

412
00:20:33.066 --> 00:20:35.110
(door opens)

413
00:20:35.194 --> 00:20:38.322
Bender.
it's for you.

414
00:20:41.325 --> 00:20:43.702
(gasps)
Assie?

415
00:20:43.785 --> 00:20:46.747
Oh. Assie.
you came home!

416
00:20:46.830 --> 00:20:50.000
You came home.

417
00:20:54.630 --> 00:20:57.633
(glass breaking.
debris clattering)

417
00:20:58.305 --> 00:21:58.843
